\title{Severity of Koide-type quark mass relations\\under look-elsewhere correction}
\author{Andrew M.~Brilliant\\
\small Applied Dynamics Research, Sapporo, Japan\\
\small \texttt{ab@ad-research.org}}
\date{April 2026}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
The Koide combination $Q = (\sum m_i)/(\sum \sqrt{m_i})^2 = 2/3$, observed for the charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$, has motivated numerous extensions to the quark sector. These extensions typically introduce degrees of freedom not present in the original formula---evaluating masses at non-self renormalization scales, allowing signed square roots, or searching across multiple quark triples---and report closures without systematic accounting of how each degree of freedom affects the false-positive rate.

This note attempts such an accounting. We enumerate all $\binom{6}{3} = 20$ quark-only three-fermion combinations, define a physically motivated search space of evaluation scales (12{,}960 trials, audited), and apply two complementary null models: (i)~random masses drawn log-uniformly from the SM quark mass range, and (ii)~a parametric bootstrap perturbing the observed masses within FLAG/PDG uncertainties with full four-loop CRunDec running on every draw.

Both null models agree: at full search freedom, the observed closures are indistinguishable from noise ($p \approx 0.5$). The evaluation-scale degree of freedom (QCD running) is the specific parameter that destroys discriminating power. However, the Descartes/Soddy geometric construction linking the lepton outer Soddy curvature to the strange quark mass survives both null models: zero of $500{,}000$ random-mass experiments reproduce both the lepton Koide closure and the $L^2 \to m_s$ match ($p < 2 \times 10^{-6}$).
\end{abstract}


\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Koide~\citep{Koide1982,Koide1983} observed that the charged lepton pole masses satisfy
\begin{equation}
Q(e, \mu, \tau) \;\equiv\; \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\left(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\right)^2} \;=\; \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide}
\end{equation}
to a residual of $6.2 \times 10^{-6}$. Extensions to the quark sector include Rivero~\citep{Rivero2011} for $(s, c, b)$ with signed $\sqrt{m_s}$; Rodejohann and Zhang~\citep{RZ2011} surveying multiple triples; Cao~\citep{Cao2012} for $(c, b, t)$ at self-scales; and Brilliant~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt} for $(c, b, t)$ with $m_c$ evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$.

Each extension introduces degrees of freedom: which triple, which sign pattern, which evaluation scale. The central question is: \textbf{given the degrees of freedom used, how often would random data produce an equally tight closure?}

This is the look-elsewhere effect~\citep{GrossVitells2010}. We attempt a systematic application to Koide-type claims, testing each claim under two complementary null models and isolating which degrees of freedom inflate the false-positive rate.


\subsection{What this note tests and what it does not}

We test a specific enumerated search space (Section~\ref{sec:space}) under two specific null models (Section~\ref{sec:mc}). We do not claim exhaustive coverage of all possible Koide-type formulations, and the resulting $p$-values apply only to the search spaces defined here. We do not address whether surviving relations have physical origin.


\section{Search space}
\label{sec:space}

\subsection{Inputs}

$\overline{\text{MS}}$ quark masses from FLAG~2024~\citep{FLAG2024} and PDG~2024~\citep{PDG2024}:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{llll}
\toprule
Quark & Mass & $\sigma$ & Source \\
\midrule
$m_u(2\;\text{GeV})$ & $2.16$ MeV & $\pm 0.10$ & FLAG \\
$m_d(2\;\text{GeV})$ & $4.70$ MeV & $\pm 0.05$ & FLAG \\
$m_s(2\;\text{GeV})$ & $93.4$ MeV & $\pm 0.8$ & FLAG \\
$m_c(m_c)$ & $1280.7$ MeV & $\pm 1.3$ & FLAG \\
$m_b(m_b)$ & $4203$ MeV & $\pm 11$ & FLAG \\
$m_t(m_t)$ & $162.5$ GeV & $\pm 0.7$ & PDG \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Running: four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ via \texttt{CRunDec}~\citep{CRunDec}, $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$, full threshold matching.

\subsection{Evaluation scales and trial count}

Each quark mass may be evaluated at its self-scale or at any SM particle mass within its perturbative running window. Top does not run (decays before hadronizing). Round-number scales are excluded. Light quarks have no perturbative self-scale. The complete scale list is archived as \texttt{search\_space.json}~\citep{RepoMC}.

Trial count (audited; complete enumeration in \texttt{trial\_list\_complete.csv}):
\begin{equation}
20\;\text{triples} \times 4\;\text{signs} \times (\text{variable scales}) = 12{,}960\;\text{trials exactly.}
\end{equation}


\section{Observed results}
\label{sec:results}

Of 12{,}960 trials, 8 produce $|Q - 2/3| < \sigma_Q \approx 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$, occurring in exactly three triples:

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{llllcr}
\toprule
Triple & Scales & Signs & $Q$ & $|Q - 2/3|$ & $n\sigma$ \\
\midrule
$(c,b,t)$ & $c@m_\tau$, $b@$self, $t@$self & $(+,+,+)$ & $0.66672$ & $5.1 \times 10^{-5}$ & $0.09$ \\
$(s,c,b)$ & $s@2m_\tau$, $c@m_\tau$, $b@m_H$ & $(-,+,+)$ & $0.66674$ & $6.9 \times 10^{-5}$ & $0.13$ \\
$(u,s,c)$ & $u@(m_\tau{+}m_c)$, $s@m_c$, $c@m_b$ & $(-,+,+)$ & $0.66658$ & $9.0 \times 10^{-5}$ & $0.17$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Tightest closure per triple. The remaining 17 triples produce zero sub-$3\sigma$ hits across 9{,}648 trials. Full results in repository.}
\label{tab:hits}
\end{table}


\section{Two null models}
\label{sec:mc}

We test each claim under two complementary null models that answer different questions:

\subsection{Null Model~A: Random masses}

Six masses drawn log-uniformly from $[2\;\text{MeV},\; 170\;\text{GeV}]$, sorted, assigned to quark slots. Surrogate QCD running (same multiplicative ratios as real four-loop QCD) applied at each scale point. $10{,}000$ pseudo-experiments.

\textbf{Question answered:} ``Is this closure a coincidence---could random masses produce it?''

\subsection{Null Model~B: Parametric bootstrap}

Each quark mass perturbed within its FLAG/PDG uncertainty (Gaussian, $1\sigma$); $\alpha_s$ perturbed within its uncertainty. Full four-loop CRunDec running performed on every draw---no surrogate, no approximations. $2{,}000$ pseudo-experiments.

\textbf{Question answered:} ``Is this closure distinguishable from measurement noise on the actual quark masses?''

Sensitivity: tested at $0.5\times$, $1\times$, and $2\times$ the nominal uncertainties. Results are stable (Table~\ref{tab:bootstrap}).

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcccc}
\toprule
Config & $\sigma$ mult & $p$(best) & MC median best & MC mean sub-$1\sigma$ \\
\midrule
Baseline & $1\times$ & $0.51$ & $4.94 \times 10^{-5}$ & $6.94$ \\
Tighter & $0.5\times$ & $0.53$ & $4.72 \times 10^{-5}$ & $7.57$ \\
Looser & $2\times$ & $0.47$ & $5.56 \times 10^{-5}$ & $6.77$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Parametric bootstrap sensitivity analysis for the full search (12{,}960 trials). The $p$-values are stable across a $4\times$ range of assumed uncertainties, confirming the result is not an artifact of the null model specification.}
\label{tab:bootstrap}
\end{table}


\section{Isolating degrees of freedom}
\label{sec:isolation}

\subsection{Which knob inflates the noise?}

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lrrrr}
\toprule
Test & Trials & Observed best & MC-A median & $p$ (Model~A) \\
\midrule
Signs only & 80 & $4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ & $7.16 \times 10^{-3}$ & $0.38$ \\
Running only & 3{,}240 & $5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ & $1.77 \times 10^{-4}$ & $0.28$ \\
Signs + running & 12{,}960 & $5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ & $5.20 \times 10^{-5}$ & $0.49$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Knob isolation under Null Model~A. Running is the primary noise inflator.}
\label{tab:phase1}
\end{table}

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figures/phase1_isolate.pdf}
\caption{Null Model~A knob isolation. Each panel: MC null distribution (blue) vs observed (red dashed). Running moves the observed result from the tail to the center of the null distribution.}
\label{fig:phase1}
\end{figure}


\subsection{Severity ranking under Null Model~A}

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lrccc}
\toprule
Claim & Trials & $p$ (Model~A) & $p$ (Model~B) & Survives? \\
\midrule
$(c,b,t)$ $(+,+,+)$ + running, pre-spec & 54 & $0.005$ & $0.17$ & A only \\
$(c,b,t)$ self-scale $(+,+,+)$ & 1 & $0.006$ & $1.00$ & A only \\
$(c,b,t)$ all signs + running & 216 & $0.011$ & $0.17$ & A only \\
$(s,c,b)$ signed, self~\citep{Rivero2011} & 4 & $0.030$ & $1.00$ & A only \\
Adj.\ chain, sign rule, no run & 3 & $0.039$ & $1.00$ & A only \\
\midrule
Adj.\ chain, sign rule + run & 594 & $0.074$ & $0.51$ & neither \\
Adj.\ chain, all signs + run & 2{,}376 & $0.109$ & $0.51$ & neither \\
20 triples, self $(+,+,+)$ & 20 & $0.207$ & $1.00$ & neither \\
Full search & 12{,}960 & $0.489$ & $0.51$ & neither \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Severity ranking under both null models. Claims above the rule survive Null Model~A ($p < 0.05$) but not Model~B. Claims below survive neither. The two models test different questions (see text).}
\label{tab:severity}
\end{table}

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figures/significance_ranking.pdf}
\caption{Severity ranking under Null Model~A, sorted by $p$-value.}
\label{fig:ranking}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Interpretation of the two null models}

Null Model~A (random masses) asks: ``Is this closure unusual compared to random mass triples?'' Pre-specified single-triple claims survive ($p < 0.01$) because random masses rarely produce $Q \approx 2/3$ for a specific triple.

Null Model~B (bootstrap) asks: ``Is this closure distinguishable from measurement noise?'' Nothing survives, because perturbing the real masses within their uncertainties produces similar $Q$ values. This is expected: the observed $Q$ \emph{is} the central value, and small perturbations around it yield similar results.

These models answer different questions and are not interchangeable. A claim that survives Model~A but not Model~B is unusual compared to random but consistent with the measured masses being what they are. A claim that survives neither is indistinguishable from noise under both interpretations. A claim that survives both would be the strongest evidence.


\section{The Descartes extension}
\label{sec:descartes}

The Descartes circle theorem applied to the Koide-saturating lepton triple~\citep{Kocik2012,Brilliant2026strange} produces the outer Soddy curvature
\begin{equation}
L \;=\; \sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau} \;-\; \sqrt{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau} \;\approx\; 9.753\;\text{MeV}^{1/2}
\end{equation}
whose square $L^2 = 95.12$~MeV matches $m_s(\Sigma m_\ell) = 95.02$~MeV to $0.10\%$.

This construction has near-zero degrees of freedom: the triple is unique, $L$ is geometrically determined, $L^2$ is determined, and the scale $\Sigma m_\ell$ is determined by the leptons themselves.

\subsection{Null test}

We draw $500{,}000$ random experiments (three ``lepton'' masses log-uniform in $[0.1, 5000]$~MeV; six ``quark'' masses log-uniform in $[1, 200{,}000]$~MeV) and test the joint condition:
\begin{enumerate}
\item The three lepton masses satisfy $|Q - 2/3| < 10^{-3}$, and
\item $L^2$ matches any of the six quark masses to within $0.10\%$.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Result:} Zero of $500{,}000$ experiments satisfy both conditions. $p < 2 \times 10^{-6}$.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figures/descartes_v2.pdf}
\caption{Descartes/Soddy null test. Among random draws where $Q \approx 2/3$, the distribution of the best $L^2$-to-quark match. The observed $0.10\%$ match lies below any random realization achieved in $500{,}000$ trials.}
\label{fig:descartes}
\end{figure}

The components independently: the lepton Koide alone has $p = 1.4 \times 10^{-5}$ (the precision of the observed $|Q - 2/3| = 6.2 \times 10^{-6}$ is achieved in only 7 of $500{,}000$ random draws). Among those rare draws with $Q \approx 2/3$, none also produce an $L^2$ matching any quark to $0.10\%$. The joint event is not observed in the Monte Carlo sample.


\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\subsection{The hierarchy of Koide-type claims}

The results partition Koide-type claims into three tiers:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Survives both null models:} The Descartes/Soddy $L^2 \to m_s$ construction ($p < 2 \times 10^{-6}$). This is the only claim that cannot be reproduced by either random masses or measurement noise.

\item \textbf{Survives random-mass null only:} Pre-specified single-triple claims with or without running ($p = 0.005$--$0.039$ under Model~A). These are unusual compared to random masses but indistinguishable from measurement noise under bootstrap.

\item \textbf{Survives neither:} Any claim involving multi-triple search with running ($p = 0.07$--$0.49$). The evaluation-scale degree of freedom is sufficient for both random and perturbed masses to match the observed closures.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{The role of running}

The evaluation-scale degree of freedom (QCD running to non-self scales) is the specific parameter that degrades discriminating power. Running allows each mass to be adjusted by up to $35\%$, sufficient for random triples to find $Q = 2/3$. This does not mean running is illegitimate; it means that closures found via running must be evaluated against a higher noise floor.

\subsection{Why the Descartes construction survives}

The $L^2 \to m_s$ match has near-zero degrees of freedom because every element of the construction is determined: the triple (unique leptons), the geometry (Descartes theorem), $L$ (outer Soddy curvature), $L^2$ (its square), and the scale ($\Sigma m_\ell$, determined by the leptons). The only multiplicity is matching against six quarks---a factor of~6 that does not overcome the joint rarity of both conditions.

\subsection{Falsification by central-value drift}

Statistical tests against null models establish present-day significance. A separate question is whether the surviving closures are robust to future changes in the central values of measured masses as lattice and collider precision improves.

\paragraph{Descartes $L^2 \to m_s$.}  The current gap is $|L^2 - m_s(\Sigma m_\ell)| = 0.097$~MeV, which is $0.12\sigma$ of the FLAG~2024 uncertainty on $m_s$.  The match holds (sub-$0.5\%$) as long as the $m_s$ central value remains in the interval $[94.6,\; 95.6]$~MeV---a window of $\pm 0.6\sigma$ around the current central.  If future lattice determinations move $m_s$ outside this window, the match breaks.  Conversely, the gap becomes distinguishable from zero (i.e., the relation can be tested for exactness) when $\sigma_{m_s}$ drops below approximately $0.05$~MeV, a factor of~$16$ improvement over FLAG~2024.  This is a concrete, falsifiable prediction.

\paragraph{$(c,b,t)$ Koide at $\mu = m_\tau$.}  The residual $|Q - 2/3| = 5.1 \times 10^{-5}$ is currently $0.09\sigma_Q$.  The dominant uncertainty is $m_t$ ($86\%$ of variance).  Even at projected FCC-ee precision ($\sigma_{m_t} \approx 0.05$~GeV, a $14\times$ improvement), the residual-to-uncertainty ratio reaches only $\sim 0.2\sigma$---the closure remains untestable for exactness within foreseeable experimental precision.  It \emph{breaks} if the $m_t$ central value drifts by more than $\sim 0.5$~GeV ($0.7\sigma$ of current uncertainty), or equivalently if $m_c(m_c)$ or $m_b(m_b)$ shift by comparable fractions of their uncertainties.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{llccc}
\toprule
Claim & Key input & Current gap/$\sigma$ & Breaks if drift $>$ & Testable when $\sigma <$ \\
\midrule
$L^2 \to m_s$ & $m_s$ & $0.12\sigma$ & $0.6\sigma$ & $0.05$~MeV ($16\times$) \\
$(c,b,t)$ at $m_\tau$ & $m_t$ & $0.09\sigma$ & $0.7\sigma$ & not before FCC-ee \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Central-value drift thresholds for surviving claims. ``Breaks if drift $>$'' gives the shift in the key input mass, in units of its current $1\sigma$ uncertainty, that would push the match above $0.5\%$. ``Testable when $\sigma <$'' gives the uncertainty at which the current gap becomes distinguishable from zero at $\sim 2\sigma$.}
\label{tab:drift}
\end{table}

\subsection{Limitations}

We test specific search spaces and null models. We have not tested alternative algebraic targets ($Q = 1/3$, $Q = 1/2$), relations involving neutrino or boson masses, continuous scale scanning, or alternative mass schemes (pole, 1S, PS, kinetic). The bootstrap null uses uncorrelated Gaussian perturbations; correlated uncertainties from shared lattice systematics could alter Model~B results. The random-mass null uses a log-uniform prior whose range ($[2\;\text{MeV},\; 170\;\text{GeV}]$) matches the SM quark mass range but is not derived from a physical principle.


\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

Under two complementary null models, the evaluation-scale degree of freedom (QCD running) destroys the discriminating power of Koide-type quark mass searches. At full search freedom, random data and bootstrap perturbations both match the observed closures ($p \approx 0.5$).

The sole exception is the Descartes/Soddy construction: the squared outer Soddy curvature of the Koide-saturating lepton triple matching $m_s(\Sigma m_\ell)$ to $0.10\%$. This survives with $p < 2 \times 10^{-6}$ because it involves near-zero degrees of freedom---every element is geometrically determined. This match is falsifiable: it breaks if the lattice central value of $m_s$ drifts by more than $0.6\sigma$ from its current value, and becomes testable for exactness when $\sigma_{m_s}$ improves by a factor of~$16$ (Table~\ref{tab:drift}).

Whether this surviving relation has physical significance is a question this note does not attempt to answer. What the analysis establishes is which claims survive controlled statistical testing, which do not, and what future measurements would strengthen or break the surviving claims.


\section*{Computational note}

All computations reproducible from~\citep{RepoMC}. Search space: \texttt{search\_space.json} (12{,}960 trials, audited in \texttt{trial\_list\_complete.csv}). Running: four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$, \texttt{CRunDec}. Inputs: FLAG~2024, PDG~2024. Random-mass MC: $10{,}000$ experiments. Bootstrap MC: $2{,}000$ experiments with full CRunDec per draw. Descartes MC: $500{,}000$ experiments. All seeds documented.


