\subsection{Interpretation of the two null models}

Null Model~A (random masses) asks: ``Is this closure unusual compared to random mass triples?'' Pre-specified single-triple claims survive ($p < 0.01$) because random masses rarely produce $Q \approx 2/3$ for a specific triple.

Null Model~B (bootstrap) asks: ``Is this closure distinguishable from measurement noise?'' Nothing survives, because perturbing the real masses within their uncertainties produces similar $Q$ values. This is expected: the observed $Q$ \emph{is} the central value, and small perturbations around it yield similar results.

These models answer different questions and are not interchangeable. A claim that survives Model~A but not Model~B is unusual compared to random but consistent with the measured masses being what they are. A claim that survives neither is indistinguishable from noise under both interpretations. A claim that survives both would be the strongest evidence.


\section{The Descartes extension}
\label{sec:descartes}

The Descartes circle theorem applied to the Koide-saturating lepton triple~\citep{Kocik2012,Brilliant2026strange} produces the outer Soddy curvature
\begin{equation}
L \;=\; \sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau} \;-\; \sqrt{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau} \;\approx\; 9.753\;\text{MeV}^{1/2}
\end{equation}
whose square $L^2 = 95.12$~MeV matches $m_s(\Sigma m_\ell) = 95.02$~MeV to $0.10\%$.

This construction has near-zero degrees of freedom: the triple is unique, $L$ is geometrically determined, $L^2$ is determined, and the scale $\Sigma m_\ell$ is determined by the leptons themselves.

\subsection{Null test}

We draw $500{,}000$ random experiments (three ``lepton'' masses log-uniform in $[0.1, 5000]$~MeV; six ``quark'' masses log-uniform in $[1, 200{,}000]$~MeV) and test the joint condition:
\begin{enumerate}
\item The three lepton masses satisfy $|Q - 2/3| < 10^{-3}$, and
\item $L^2$ matches any of the six quark masses to within $0.10\%$.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Result:} Zero of $500{,}000$ experiments satisfy both conditions. $p < 2 \times 10^{-6}$.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figures/descartes_v2.pdf}
\caption{Descartes/Soddy null test. Among random draws where $Q \approx 2/3$, the distribution of the best $L^2$-to-quark match. The observed $0.10\%$ match lies below any random realization achieved in $500{,}000$ trials.}
\label{fig:descartes}
\end{figure}

The components independently: the lepton Koide alone has $p = 1.4 \times 10^{-5}$ (the precision of the observed $|Q - 2/3| = 6.2 \times 10^{-6}$ is achieved in only 7 of $500{,}000$ random draws). Among those rare draws with $Q \approx 2/3$, none also produce an $L^2$ matching any quark to $0.10\%$. The joint event is not observed in the Monte Carlo sample.


\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\subsection{The hierarchy of Koide-type claims}

The results partition Koide-type claims into three tiers:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Survives both null models:} The Descartes/Soddy $L^2 \to m_s$ construction ($p < 2 \times 10^{-6}$). This is the only claim that cannot be reproduced by either random masses or measurement noise.

\item \textbf{Survives random-mass null only:} Pre-specified single-triple claims with or without running ($p = 0.005$--$0.039$ under Model~A). These are unusual compared to random masses but indistinguishable from measurement noise under bootstrap.

\item \textbf{Survives neither:} Any claim involving multi-triple search with running ($p = 0.07$--$0.49$). The evaluation-scale degree of freedom is sufficient for both random and perturbed masses to match the observed closures.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{The role of running}

The evaluation-scale degree of freedom (QCD running to non-self scales) is the specific parameter that degrades discriminating power. Running allows each mass to be adjusted by up to $35\%$, sufficient for random triples to find $Q = 2/3$. This does not mean running is illegitimate; it means that closures found via running must be evaluated against a higher noise floor.

\subsection{Why the Descartes construction survives}

The $L^2 \to m_s$ match has near-zero degrees of freedom because every element of the construction is determined: the triple (unique leptons), the geometry (Descartes theorem), $L$ (outer Soddy curvature), $L^2$ (its square), and the scale ($\Sigma m_\ell$, determined by the leptons). The only multiplicity is matching against six quarks---a factor of~6 that does not overcome the joint rarity of both conditions.

\subsection{Falsification by central-value drift}

Statistical tests against null models establish present-day significance. A separate question is whether the surviving closures are robust to future changes in the central values of measured masses as lattice and collider precision improves.

\paragraph{Descartes $L^2 \to m_s$.}  The current gap is $|L^2 - m_s(\Sigma m_\ell)| = 0.097$~MeV, which is $0.12\sigma$ of the FLAG~2024 uncertainty on $m_s$.  The match holds (sub-$0.5\%$) as long as the $m_s$ central value remains in the interval $[94.6,\; 95.6]$~MeV---a window of $\pm 0.6\sigma$ around the current central.  If future lattice determinations move $m_s$ outside this window, the match breaks.  Conversely, the gap becomes distinguishable from zero (i.e., the relation can be tested for exactness) when $\sigma_{m_s}$ drops below approximately $0.05$~MeV, a factor of~$16$ improvement over FLAG~2024.  This is a concrete, falsifiable prediction.

