\subsection{Limitations}

We test specific search spaces and null models. We have not tested alternative algebraic targets ($Q = 1/3$, $Q = 1/2$), relations involving neutrino or boson masses, continuous scale scanning, or alternative mass schemes (pole, 1S, PS, kinetic). The bootstrap null uses uncorrelated Gaussian perturbations; correlated uncertainties from shared lattice systematics could alter Model~B results. The random-mass null uses a log-uniform prior whose range ($[2\;\text{MeV},\; 170\;\text{GeV}]$) matches the SM quark mass range but is not derived from a physical principle.


\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

Under two complementary null models, the evaluation-scale degree of freedom (QCD running) destroys the discriminating power of Koide-type quark mass searches. At full search freedom, random data and bootstrap perturbations both match the observed closures ($p \approx 0.5$).

The sole exception is the Descartes/Soddy construction: the squared outer Soddy curvature of the Koide-saturating lepton triple matching $m_s(\Sigma m_\ell)$ to $0.10\%$. This survives with $p < 2 \times 10^{-6}$ because it involves near-zero degrees of freedom---every element is geometrically determined. This match is falsifiable: it breaks if the lattice central value of $m_s$ drifts by more than $0.6\sigma$ from its current value, and becomes testable for exactness when $\sigma_{m_s}$ improves by a factor of~$16$ (Table~\ref{tab:drift}).

Whether this surviving relation has physical significance is a question this note does not attempt to answer. What the analysis establishes is which claims survive controlled statistical testing, which do not, and what future measurements would strengthen or break the surviving claims.


